# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: x-ray-crystallography-protein
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Although the term is used in the field of optics to describe light and other electromagnetic waves, dispersion in the same sense can apply to any sort of wave motion such as acoustic dispersion in the case of sound and seismic waves, and in gravity waves (ocean waves).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Within optics, dispersion is a property of telecommunication signals along transmission lines (such as microwaves in coaxial cable) or the pulses of light in optical fiber.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In optics, one important and familiar consequence of dispersion is the change in the angle of refraction of different colors of light, as seen in the spectrum produced by a dispersive prism and in chromatic aberration of lenses.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Design of compound achromatic lenses, in which chromatic aberration is largely cancelled, uses a quantification of a glass's dispersion given by its Abbe number *V*, where *lower* Abbe numbers correspond to *greater* dispersion over the visible spectrum.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In some applications such as telecommunications, the absolute phase of a wave is often not important but only the propagation of wave packets or "pulses"; in that case one is interested only in variations of group velocity with frequency, so-called group-velocity dispersion.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Dispersion causes a rainbow's spatial separation of a white light into components of different wavelengths (different colors).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] However, dispersion also has an effect in many other circumstances: for example, group-velocity dispersion causes pulses to spread in optical fibers, degrading signals over long distances; also, a cancellation between group-velocity dispersion and nonlinear effects leads to soliton waves.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Most often, chromatic dispersion refers to bulk material dispersion, that is, the change in refractive index with optical frequency.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] However, in a waveguide there is also the phenomenon of *waveguide dispersion*, in which case a wave's phase velocity in a structure depends on its frequency simply due to the structure's geometry.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] More generally, "waveguide" dispersion can occur for waves propagating through any inhomogeneous structure (e.g., a photonic crystal), whether or not the waves are confined to some region.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In a waveguide, *both* types of dispersion will generally be present, although they are not strictly additive.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] For example, in fiber optics the material and waveguide dispersion can effectively cancel each other out to produce a zero-dispersion wavelength, important for fast fiber-optic communication.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Material dispersion can be a desirable or undesirable effect in optical applications.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The dispersion of light by glass prisms is used to construct spectrometers and spectroradiometers.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] However, in lenses, dispersion causes chromatic aberration, an undesired effect that may degrade images in microscopes, telescopes, and photographic objectives.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] where *c* is the speed of light in vacuum, and *n* is the refractive index of the medium.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In general, the refractive index is some function of the frequency *f* of the light, thus *n* = *n*(*f*), or alternatively, with respect to the wave's wavelength *n* = *n*(*λ*).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The wavelength dependence of a material's refractive index is usually quantified by its Abbe number or its coefficients in an empirical formula such as the Cauchy or Sellmeier equations.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Because of the Kramers–Kronig relations, the wavelength dependence of the real part of the refractive index is related to the material absorption, described by the imaginary part of the refractive index (also called the extinction coefficient).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In particular, for non-magnetic materials (*μ* = *μ*0), the susceptibility *χ* that appears in the Kramers–Kronig relations is the electric susceptibility *χ*e = *n*2 − 1.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The most commonly seen consequence of dispersion in optics is the separation of white light into a color spectrum by a prism.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] From Snell's law it can be seen that the angle of refraction of light in a prism depends on the refractive index of the prism material.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Since that refractive index varies with wavelength, it follows that the angle that the light is refracted by will also vary with wavelength, causing an angular separation of the colors known as *angular dispersion*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In this case, the medium is said to have *normal dispersion*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] However, if the index increases with increasing wavelength (which is typically the case in the ultraviolet), the medium is said to have *anomalous dispersion*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] At the interface of such a material with air or vacuum (index of ~1), Snell's law predicts that light incident at an angle *θ* to the normal will be refracted at an angle arcsin(⁠sin *θ*/*n*⁠).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Thus, in the case of normal dispersion, blue light, with a higher refractive index, will be bent more strongly than red light, resulting in the well-known rainbow pattern.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Beyond simply describing a change in the phase velocity over wavelength, a more serious consequence of dispersion in many applications is termed group-velocity dispersion (GVD).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] While phase velocity *v* is defined as *v* = *c*/*n*, this describes only one frequency component.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] When different frequency components are combined, as when considering a signal or a pulse, one is often more interested in the group velocity, which describes the speed at which a pulse or information superimposed on a wave (modulation) propagates.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In the accompanying animation, it can be seen that the wave itself (orange-brown) travels at a phase velocity much faster than the speed of the *envelope* (black), which corresponds to the group velocity.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] This pulse might be a communications signal, for instance, and its information only travels at the group velocity rate, even though it consists of wavefronts advancing at a faster rate (the phase velocity).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] It is possible to calculate the group velocity from the refractive-index curve *n*(*ω*) or more directly from the wavenumber *k* = *ωn*/*c*, where *ω* is the radian frequency *ω* = 2*πf*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Whereas one expression for the phase velocity is *v*p = *ω*/*k*, the group velocity can be expressed using the derivative: *v*g = *dω*/*dk*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] When dispersion is present, not only the group velocity is not equal to the phase velocity, but generally it itself varies with wavelength.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] This is known as group-velocity dispersion and causes a short pulse of light to be broadened, as the different-frequency components within the pulse travel at different velocities.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Group-velocity dispersion is quantified as the derivative of the *reciprocal* of the group velocity with respect to angular frequency, which results in *group-velocity dispersion* = *d*2*k*/*dω*2.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] If a light pulse is propagated through a material with positive group-velocity dispersion, then the shorter-wavelength components travel slower than the longer-wavelength components.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The pulse therefore becomes *positively chirped*, or *up-chirped*, increasing in frequency with time.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] On the other hand, if a pulse travels through a material with negative group-velocity dispersion, shorter-wavelength components travel faster than the longer ones, and the pulse becomes *negatively chirped*, or *down-chirped*, decreasing in frequency with time.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] An everyday example of a negatively chirped signal in the acoustic domain is that of an approaching train hitting deformities on a welded track.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The sound caused by the train itself is impulsive and travels much faster in the metal tracks than in air, so that the train can be heard well before it arrives.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] However, from afar it is not heard as causing impulses, but leads to a distinctive descending chirp, amidst reverberation caused by the complexity of the vibrational modes of the track.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Group-velocity dispersion can be heard in that the volume of the sounds stays audible for a surprisingly long time, up to several seconds.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The result of GVD, whether negative or positive, is ultimately temporal spreading of the pulse.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] This makes dispersion management extremely important in optical communications systems based on optical fiber, since if dispersion is too high, a group of pulses representing a bit-stream will spread in time and merge, rendering the bit-stream unintelligible.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] This limits the length of fiber that a signal can be sent down without regeneration.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] One possible answer to this problem is to send signals down the optical fibre at a wavelength where the GVD is zero (e.g., around 1.3–1.5 μm in silica fibres), so pulses at this wavelength suffer minimal spreading from dispersion.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In practice, however, this approach causes more problems than it solves because zero GVD unacceptably amplifies other nonlinear effects (such as four-wave mixing).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Another possible option is to use soliton pulses in the regime of negative dispersion, a form of optical pulse which uses a nonlinear optical effect to self-maintain its shape.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Solitons have the practical problem, however, that they require a certain power level to be maintained in the pulse for the nonlinear effect to be of the correct strength.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Dispersion control is also important in lasers that produce short pulses.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The overall dispersion of the optical resonator is a major factor in determining the duration of the pulses emitted by the laser.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] A pair of prisms can be arranged to produce net negative dispersion, which can be used to balance the usually positive dispersion of the laser medium.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Diffraction gratings can also be used to produce dispersive effects; these are often used in high-power laser amplifier systems.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Recently, an alternative to prisms and gratings has been developed: chirped mirrors.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] These dielectric mirrors are coated so that different wavelengths have different penetration lengths, and therefore different group delays.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The coating layers can be tailored to achieve a net negative dispersion.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Waveguides are highly dispersive due to their geometry (rather than just to their material composition).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Optical fibers are a sort of waveguide for optical frequencies (light) widely used in modern telecommunications systems.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The rate at which data can be transported on a single fiber is limited by pulse broadening due to chromatic dispersion among other phenomena.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] where *λ* = 2π*c*/*ω* is the vacuum wavelength, and *v*g = *dω*/*dβ* is the group velocity.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] This formula generalizes the one in the previous section for homogeneous media and includes both waveguide dispersion and material dispersion.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The reason for defining the dispersion in this way is that |*D*| is the (asymptotic) temporal pulse spreading Δ*t* per unit bandwidth Δ*λ* per unit distance travelled, commonly reported in ps/(nm⋅km) for optical fibers.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In the case of multi-mode optical fibers, so-called modal dispersion will also lead to pulse broadening.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Even in single-mode fibers, pulse broadening can occur as a result of polarization mode dispersion (since there are still two polarization modes).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] These are *not* examples of chromatic dispersion, as they are not dependent on the wavelength or bandwidth of the pulses propagated.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In particular, the dispersion parameter *D* defined above is obtained from only one derivative of the group velocity.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Higher derivatives are known as *higher-order dispersion*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] These terms are simply a Taylor series expansion of the dispersion relation *β*(*ω*) of the medium or waveguide around some particular frequency.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In electromagnetics and optics, the term *dispersion* generally refers to aforementioned temporal or frequency dispersion.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Spatial dispersion refers to the non-local response of the medium to the space; this can be reworded as the wavevector dependence of the permittivity.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] where the kernel $f_{ik}$ is dielectric response (susceptibility); its indices make it in general a tensor to account for the anisotropy of the medium.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Spatial dispersion is negligible in most macroscopic cases, where the scale of variation of $E_{k}(t-\tau ,r')$ is much larger than atomic dimensions, because the dielectric kernel dies out at macroscopic distances.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Nevertheless, it can result in non-negligible macroscopic effects, particularly in conducting media such as metals, electrolytes and plasmas.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Spatial dispersion also plays role in optical activity and Doppler broadening, as well as in the theory of metamaterials.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Fire is a colloquial term used by gemologists to describe a gemstone's dispersive nature or lack thereof.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] The amount of fire demonstrated by a given gemstone is a function of the gemstone's facet angles, the polish quality, the lighting environment, the material's refractive index, the saturation of color, and the orientation of the viewer relative to the gemstone.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] In photographic and microscopic lenses, dispersion causes chromatic aberration, which causes the different colors in the image not to overlap properly.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Various techniques have been developed to counteract this, such as the use of achromats, multielement lenses with glasses of different dispersion.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] They are constructed in such a way that the chromatic aberrations of the different parts cancel out.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Pulsars are spinning neutron stars that emit pulses at very regular intervals ranging from milliseconds to seconds.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Astronomers believe that the pulses are emitted simultaneously over a wide range of frequencies.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] However, as observed on Earth, the components of each pulse emitted at higher radio frequencies arrive before those emitted at lower frequencies.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] This dispersion occurs because of the ionized component of the interstellar medium, mainly the free electrons, which make the group velocity frequency-dependent.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] with units of parsecs per cubic centimetre (1 pc/cm3 = 30.857×1021 m−2).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Typically for astronomical observations, this delay cannot be measured directly, since the emission time is unknown.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] What *can* be measured is the difference in arrival times at two different frequencies.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] Rewriting the above equation in terms of Δ*t* allows one to determine the DM by measuring pulse arrival times at multiple frequencies.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/anomalous-dispersion] This in turn can be used to study the interstellar medium, as well as allow observations of pulsars at different frequencies to be combined.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] In many areas of science, **Bragg's law** – also known as **Wulff–Bragg's condition** or **Laue–Bragg interference** – is a special case of Laue diffraction that gives the angles for coherent scattering of waves from a large crystal lattice.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] It describes how the superposition of wave fronts scattered by lattice planes leads to a strict relation between the wavelength and scattering angle.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] This law was initially formulated for X-rays, but it also applies to all types of matter waves including neutron and electron waves if there are a large number of atoms, as well as to visible light with artificial periodic microscale lattices.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] They found that these crystals, at certain specific wavelengths and incident angles, produced intense peaks of reflected radiation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Lawrence Bragg explained this result by modeling the crystal as a set of discrete parallel planes separated by a constant parameter d.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] He proposed that the incident X-ray radiation would produce a Bragg peak if reflections off the various planes interfered constructively.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] The interference is constructive when the phase difference between the wave reflected off different atomic planes is a multiple of 2*π*; this condition (see *Bragg condition* section below) was first presented by Lawrence Bragg on 11 November 1912 to the Cambridge Philosophical Society.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Due to its simplicity, Bragg's law provided a powerful new tool for determining crystal lattices from X-ray diffraction data.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Lawrence Bragg and his father, William Henry Bragg, were awarded the Nobel Prize in physics in 1915 for their work in solving crystal structures beginning with NaCl, ZnS, and diamond.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] They are the only father-son team to jointly win.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] The concept of Bragg diffraction applies equally to neutron diffraction and approximately to electron diffraction.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] In both cases the wavelengths are comparable with inter-atomic distances (~ 150 pm).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Many other types of matter waves have also been shown to diffract, and also light from objects with a larger ordered structure such as opals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Bragg diffraction occurs when radiation of a wavelength λ comparable to atomic spacings is scattered in a specular fashion (mirror-like reflection) by planes of atoms in a crystalline material, and undergoes constructive interference.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] When the scattered waves are incident at a specific angle, they remain in phase and constructively interfere.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] This equation, Bragg's law, describes the condition on *θ* for constructive interference.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] A map of the intensities of the scattered waves as a function of their angle is called a diffraction pattern.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Strong intensities known as Bragg peaks are obtained in the diffraction pattern when the scattering angles satisfy Bragg condition.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] This is a special case of the more general Laue equations, and the Laue equations can be shown to reduce to the Bragg condition with additional assumptions.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] In Bragg's original paper he describes his approach as a Huygens's construction for a reflected wave.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Suppose that a plane wave (of any type) is incident on planes of lattice points, with separation d , at an angle $\theta$ as shown in the Figure.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Points **A** and **C** are on one plane, and **B** is on the plane below.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] There will be a path difference between the ray that gets reflected along **AC'** and the ray that gets transmitted along **AB**, then reflected along **BC**.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] where n and $\lambda$ are an integer and the wavelength of the incident wave respectively.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] which simplifies to $n\lambda =2d\sin \theta \,,$ which is Bragg's law shown above.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] If only two planes of atoms were diffracting, as shown in the Figure then the transition from constructive to destructive interference would be gradual as a function of angle, with gentle maxima at the Bragg angles.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] However, since many atomic planes are participating in most real materials, sharp peaks are typical.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] A rigorous derivation from the more general Laue equations is available (see page: Laue equations).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] The Bragg condition is correct for very large crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Because the scattering of X-rays and neutrons is relatively weak, in many cases quite large crystals with sizes of 100 nm or more are used.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] While there can be additional effects due to crystal defects, these are often quite small.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] In contrast, electrons interact thousands of times more strongly with solids than X-rays, and also lose energy (inelastic scattering).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Therefore, samples used in transmission electron diffraction are much thinner.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Typical diffraction patterns, for instance the Figure, show spots for different directions (plane waves) of the electrons leaving a crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] The angles that Bragg's law predicts are still approximately right, but in general there is a lattice of spots which are close to projections of the reciprocal lattice that is at right angles to the direction of the electron beam.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] (In contrast, Bragg's law predicts that only one or perhaps two would be present, not simultaneously tens to hundreds.) With low-energy electron diffraction where the electron energies are typically 30-1000 electron volts, the result is similar with the electrons reflected back from a surface.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Also similar is reflection high-energy electron diffraction which typically leads to rings of diffraction spots.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] With X-rays the effect of having small crystals is described by the Scherrer equation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] This leads to broadening of the Bragg peaks which can be used to estimate the size of the crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] A colloidal crystal is a highly ordered array of particles that forms over a long range (from a few millimeters to one centimeter in length); colloidal crystals have appearance and properties roughly analogous to their atomic or molecular counterparts.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Periodic arrays of spherical particles give rise to interstitial voids (the spaces between the particles), which act as a natural diffraction grating for visible light waves, when the interstitial spacing is of the same order of magnitude as the incident lightwave.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] In these cases brilliant iridescence (or play of colours) is attributed to the diffraction and constructive interference of visible lightwaves according to Bragg's law, in a matter analogous to the scattering of X-rays in crystalline solid.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] The effects occur at visible wavelengths because the interplanar spacing d is much larger than for true crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Precious opal is one example of a colloidal crystal with optical effects.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Volume Bragg gratings (VBG) or volume holographic gratings (VHG) consist of a volume where there is a periodic change in the refractive index.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Depending on the orientation of the refractive index modulation, VBG can be used either to transmit or reflect a small bandwidth of wavelengths.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] where m is the Bragg order (a positive integer), *λ*B the diffracted wavelength, Λ the fringe spacing of the grating, θ the angle between the incident beam and the normal (**N**) of the entrance surface and φ the angle between the normal and the grating vector (**KG**).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Radiation that does not match Bragg's law will pass through the VBG undiffracted.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] The output wavelength can be tuned over a few hundred nanometers by changing the incident angle (θ).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] VBG are being used to produce widely tunable laser source or perform global hyperspectral imagery (see Photon etc.).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] The measurement of the angles can be used to determine crystal structure, see x-ray crystallography for more details.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] where a is the lattice spacing of the cubic crystal, and h, k, and ℓ are the Miller indices of the Bragg plane.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] One can derive selection rules for the Miller indices for different cubic Bravais lattices as well as many others, a few of the selection rules are given in the table below.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] These selection rules can be used for any crystal with the given crystal structure.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] KCl has a face-centered cubic Bravais lattice.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] However, the K+ and the Cl− ion have the same number of electrons and are quite close in size, so that the diffraction pattern becomes essentially the same as for a simple cubic structure with half the lattice parameter.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Selection rules for other structures can be referenced elsewhere, or derived.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/bragg-s-law] Lattice spacing for the other crystal systems can be found here.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] With usual detectors the intensity $I=F\cdot F^{*}$ is being measured, and all the information about phase ( $\Phi$ ) is lost.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] Then, in the absence of phases (Φ), we are unable to complete the shown Fourier transform relating the experimental data from X-ray crystallography (in reciprocal space) to real-space electron density, into which the atomic model is built.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] MR tries to find the model which fits best experimental intensities among known structures.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] We can derive a Patterson map for the intensities, which is an interatomic vector map created by squaring the structure factor amplitudes and setting all phases to zero.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] This vector map contains a peak for each atom related to every other atom, with a large peak at 0,0,0, where vectors relating atoms to themselves "pile up".
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] This principle lies at the heart of MR, and can allow us to infer information about the orientation and location of an unknown molecule with its unit cell.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] Due to historic limitations in computing power, an MR search is typically divided into two steps: rotation and translation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] In the rotation function, our unknown Patterson map is compared to Patterson maps derived from our known homologue structure in different orientations.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] Historically r-factors and/or correlation coefficients were used to score the rotation function, however, modern programs use maximum likelihood-based algorithms.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] The highest correlation (and therefore scores) are obtained when the two structures (known and unknown) are in similar orientation(s)—these can then be output in Euler angles or spherical polar angles.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] In the translation function, the now correctly oriented known model can be correctly positioned by translating it to the correct co-ordinates within the asymmetric unit.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] This is accomplished by moving the model, calculating a new Patterson map, and comparing it to the unknown-derived Patterson map.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] This brute-force search is computationally expensive and fast translation functions are now more commonly used.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] Positions with high correlations are output in Cartesian coordinates.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] With the improvement of *de novo* protein structure prediction, many protocols including MR-Rosetta, QUARK, AWSEM-Suite and I-TASSER-MR can generate a lot of native-like decoy structures that are useful to solve the phase problem by molecular replacement.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] Following this, we should have correctly oriented and translated phasing models, from which we can derive phases which are (hopefully) accurate enough to derive electron density maps.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/molecular-replacement] These can be used to build and refine an atomic model of our unknown structure.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] In the process of protein crystallization, proteins are dissolved in an aqueous environment and sample solution until they reach the supersaturated state.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Different methods are used to reach that state such as vapor diffusion, microbatch, microdialysis, and free-interface diffusion.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Developing protein crystals is a difficult process influenced by many factors, including pH, temperature, ionic strength in the crystallization solution, and even gravity.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Once formed, these crystals can be used in structural biology to study the molecular structure of the protein, particularly for various industrial or medical purposes.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] For over 150 years, scientists from all around the world have known about the crystallization of protein molecules.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] In 1840, Friedrich Ludwig Hünefeld accidentally discovered the formation of crystalline material in samples of earthworm blood held under two glass slides and occasionally observed small plate-like crystals in desiccated swine or human blood samples.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] These crystals were named as 'haemoglobin', by Felix Hoppe-Seyler in 1864.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The seminal findings of Hünefeld inspired many scientists in the future.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] In 1851, Otto Funke described the process of producing human haemoglobin crystals by diluting red blood cells with solvents, such as pure water, alcohol or ether, followed by slow evaporation of the solvent from the protein solution.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Preyer, Professor at University of Jena, published a book entitled *Die Blutkrystalle* (The Crystals of Blood), reviewing the features of haemoglobin crystals from around 50 species of mammals, birds, reptiles and fishes.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] These early approaches relied on simple evaporation techniques and worked mainly with naturally abundant proteins such as hemoglobin.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Reichert, together with the mineralogist Amos P.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Brown, published a treatise on the preparation, physiology and geometrical characterization of hemeoglobin crystals from several hundreds animals, including extinct species such as the Tasmanian wolf.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] In 1934, John Desmond Bernal and his student Dorothy Hodgkin discovered that protein crystals surrounded by their mother liquor (the remaining solution after a protein has crystallized out of a supersaturated solution) gave better diffraction patterns than dried crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Using pepsin, they were the first to discern the diffraction pattern of a wet, globular protein.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Prior to Bernal and Hodgkin, protein crystallography had only been performed in dry conditions with inconsistent and unreliable results.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] This is the first X‐ray diffraction pattern of a protein crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] In 1958, the structure of myoglobin (a red protein containing heme), determined by X-ray crystallography, was first reported by John Kendrew.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Kendrew shared the 1962 Nobel Prize in Chemistry with Max Perutz for this discovery.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Protein crystallization is governed by the same physics that governs the formation of inorganic crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] For crystallization to occur spontaneously, the crystal state must be favored thermodynamically.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] This is described by the Gibbs free energy (∆G), defined as ∆G = ∆H- T∆S, which captures how the enthalpy change of a process, ∆H, trades off with the corresponding change in entropy, ∆S.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Entropy, roughly, describes the disorder of a system.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Highly ordered states, such as protein crystals, are disfavored thermodynamically compared to more disordered states, such as solutions of proteins in solvent, because the transition to a more ordered state would decrease the total entropy of the system (negative ∆S).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] For crystals to form spontaneously, the ∆G of crystal formation must be negative.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] In other words, the entropic penalty must be paid by a corresponding decrease in the total energy of the system (∆H).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Familiar inorganic crystals such as sodium chloride spontaneously form at ambient conditions because the crystal state decreases the total energy of the system.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] However, crystallization of some proteins under ambient conditions would both decrease the entropy (negative ∆S) and increase the total energy (positive ∆H) of the system, and thus does not occur spontaneously.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] To achieve crystallization of such proteins conditions are modified to make crystal formation energetically favorable.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] This is often accomplished by creation of a supersaturated solution of the sample.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Crystal formation requires two steps: nucleation and growth.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Nucleation is the initiation step for crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] At the nucleation phase, protein molecules in solution come together as aggregates to form a stable solid nucleus.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] As the nucleus forms, the crystal grows bigger and bigger by molecules attaching to this stable nucleus.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The nucleation step is critical for crystal formation since it is the first-order phase transition of samples moving from having a high degree of freedom to obtaining an ordered state (aqueous to solid).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] For the nucleation step to succeed, the manipulation of crystallization parameters is essential.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The approach behind getting a protein to crystallize is to yield a lower solubility of the targeted protein in solution.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Once the solubility limit is exceeded and crystals are present, crystallization is accomplished.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Vapor diffusion is the most commonly employed method of protein crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] In this method, droplets containing purified protein, buffer, and precipitant are allowed to equilibrate with a larger reservoir containing similar buffers and precipitants in higher concentrations.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Initially, the droplet of protein solution contains comparatively low precipitant and protein concentrations, but as the drop and reservoir equilibrate, the precipitant and protein concentrations increase in the drop.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] If the appropriate crystallization solutions are used for a given protein, crystal growth occurs in the drop.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] This method is used because it allows for gentle and gradual changes in concentration of protein and precipitant concentration, which aid in the growth of large and well-ordered crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Vapor diffusion can be performed in either hanging-drop or sitting-drop format.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Hanging-drop apparatus involve a drop of protein solution placed on an inverted cover slip, which is then suspended above the reservoir.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Sitting-drop crystallization apparatus place the drop on a pedestal that is separated from the reservoir.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Both of these methods require sealing of the environment so that equilibration between the drop and reservoir can occur.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] A microbatch usually involves immersing a very small volume of protein droplets in oil (as little as 1 μL).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The reason that oil is required is because such low volume of protein solution is used and therefore evaporation must be inhibited to carry out the experiment aqueously.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Although there are various oils that can be used, the two most common sealing agent are paraffin oils (described by Chayen et al.) and silicon oils (described by D'Arcy).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] There are also other methods for microbatching that do not use a liquid sealing agent and instead require a scientist to quickly place a film or some tape on a welled plate after placing the drop in the well.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Besides the very limited amounts of sample needed, this method also has as a further advantage that the samples are protected from airborne contamination, as they are never exposed to the air during the experiment.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Microdialysis takes advantage of a semi-permeable membrane, across which small molecules and ions can pass, while proteins and large polymers cannot cross.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] By establishing a gradient of solute concentration across the membrane and allowing the system to progress toward equilibrium, the system can slowly move toward supersaturation, at which point protein crystals may form.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Microdialysis can produce crystals by salting out, employing high concentrations of salt or other small membrane-permeable compounds that decrease the solubility of the protein.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Very occasionally, some proteins can be crystallized by dialysis salting in, by dialyzing against pure water, removing solutes, driving self-association and crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] This technique brings together protein and precipitation solutions without premixing them, but instead, injecting them through either sides of a channel, allowing equilibrium through diffusion.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The two solutions come into contact in a reagent chamber, both at their maximum concentrations, initiating spontaneous nucleation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] As the system comes into equilibrium, the level of supersaturation decreases, favouring crystal growth.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The basic driving force for protein crystallization is to optimize the number of bonds one can form with another protein through intermolecular interactions.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] These interactions depend on electron densities of molecules and the protein side chains that change as a function of pH.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The tertiary and quaternary structure of proteins are determined by intermolecular interactions between the amino acids' side groups, in which the hydrophilic groups are usually facing outwards to the solution to form a hydration shell to the solvent (water).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] As the pH changes, the charge on these polar side group also change with respect to the solution pH and the protein's pKa.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Hence, the choice of pH is essential either to promote the formation of crystals where the bonding between molecules to each other is more favorable than with water molecules. pH is one of the most powerful manipulations that one can assign for the optimal crystallization condition.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Temperature is another interesting parameter to discuss since protein solubility is a function of temperature.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] In protein crystallization, manipulation of temperature to yield successful crystals is one common strategy.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Unlike pH, temperature of different components of the crystallography experiments could impact the final results such as temperature of buffer preparation, temperature of the actual crystallization experiment, etc.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Chemical additives are small chemical compounds that are added to the crystallization process to increase the yield of crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The role of small molecules in protein crystallization had not been well thought of in the early days since they were thought of as contaminants in most case.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Small molecules are thought to help if/when they are incorporated as "packing bridges" in the crystal contact interfaces.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] It is currently not possible (as of 2017) to rationally determine what small molecules to use to improve chances of crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] A classic way to crystalize is by adding a small amount of protease to the droplet, as digestion may yield a more crystallizable fragment by removing unstructured regions.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Chemical modification can be used to improve crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The most commonly used is reductive methylation, which changes surface lysines in a way that usually reduces entropy.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] High through-put methods exist to help streamline the large number of experiments required to explore the various conditions that are necessary for successful crystal growth.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] There are numerous commercial kits available for order which apply preassembled ingredients in systems guaranteed to produce successful crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Using such a kit, a scientist avoids the hassle of purifying a protein and determining the appropriate crystallization conditions.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Liquid-handling robots can be used to set up and automate large number of crystallization experiments simultaneously.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] What would otherwise be slow and potentially error-prone process carried out by a human can be accomplished efficiently and accurately with an automated system.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Robotic crystallization systems use the same components described above, but carry out each step of the procedure quickly and with a large number of replicates.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Each experiment utilizes tiny amounts of solution, and the advantage of the smaller size is two-fold: the smaller sample sizes not only cut-down on expenditure of purified protein, but smaller amounts of solution lead to quicker crystallizations.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Each experiment is monitored by a camera which detects crystal growth.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Proteins can be engineered to improve the chance of successful protein crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] A common way is by trimming the recombinant construct to remove N- and C- terminal parts, which are frequently disordered or poorly structured ("high entropy").
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Surface entropy reduction entails replacing surface residue clusters with high conformational entropy (usually lysine, glutamate, and glutamine) with alanines.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] In a similar vein, replacing lysine with arginine in bulk has proven useful.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] It is also possible to engineer in crystal contacts by mutating residues.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] An even more advanced method involves the use of "chaperone" proteins known to be more crystallizable.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] This can be achieved by designing a fusion protein consisting of the protein with unknown structure and a protein domain known to crystalize well.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The interaction in question can also be *intermolecular*, for example between the candidate protein and some antibody Fab fragments selected to bind tightly to the protein, or between a candidate-maltose-binding protein (MBP) fusion and a protein specifically designed to bind MBP.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Many methods for protein engineering require some forward knowledge of protein structure, either simply knowing what residues are surface or buried or knowing the full tertiary structure.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Modern protein structure prediction tools are largely sufficient.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] It is also possible to predict the result of crystallization using these methods.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Cystine residues on the surface tend to cause trouble for recombinant protein production by causing aggregation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] This is not an issue with crystallization *per se*, but is commonly encountered with structure determination nevertheless.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Crystallization of proteins can also be useful in the formulation of proteins for pharmaceutical purposes.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] Crystallization allows for the formation and purification of many active pharmaceutical ingredients.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/protein-crystallization] The generating of solid particles with desired crystal form and purity is crucial for controlling the physiochemical properties (the physical and chemical characteristics of a substance, such as solubility, density, pH, and stability) of proteins.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] In other words, it is a measure of how well the refined structure predicts the observed data.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] The value is also sometimes called the **discrepancy index**, as it mathematically describes the difference between the experimental observations and the ideal calculated values.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] where *F* is the so-called structure factor and the sum extends over all the reflections of X-rays measured and their calculated counterparts respectively.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] The minimum possible value is zero, indicating perfect agreement between experimental observations and the structure factors predicted from the model.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] There is no theoretical maximum, but in practice, values are considerably less than one even for poor models, provided the model includes a suitable scale factor.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] Random experimental errors in the data contribute to R even for a perfect model, and these have more leverage when the data are weak or few, such as for a low-resolution data set.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] Model inadequacies such as incorrect or missing parts and unmodeled disorder are the other main contributors to R , making it useful to assess the progress and final result of a crystallographic model refinement.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] For large molecules, the R-factor usually ranges between 0.6 (when computed for a random model and against an experimental data set) and 0.2 (for example for a well refined macro-molecular model at a resolution of 2.5 Ångström).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] 1000 atoms) usually form better-ordered crystals than large molecules, and thus it is possible to attain lower R-factors.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] In the Cambridge Structural Database of small-molecule structures, more than 95% of the 500,000+ crystals have an R-factor lower than 0.15, and 9.5% have an R-factor lower than 0.03.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] If the two statistics differ significantly then that indicates the model has been over-parameterized, so that to some extent it predicts not the ideal error-free data for the correct model, but rather the error-afflicted data actually observed.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/r-factor-crystallography] The quantities $R_{\text{sym}}$ and $R_{\text{merge}}$ are similarly used to describe the internal agreement of measurements in a crystallographic data set.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In condensed matter physics and crystallography, the **static structure factor** (or **structure factor** for short) is a mathematical description of how a material scatters incident radiation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The structure factor is a critical tool in the interpretation of scattering patterns (interference patterns) obtained in X-ray, electron and neutron diffraction experiments.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Confusingly, there are two different mathematical expressions in use, both called 'structure factor'.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] One is usually written $S(\mathbf {q} )$ ; it is more generally valid, and relates the observed diffracted intensity per atom to that produced by a single scattering unit.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The other is usually written F or $F_{hk\ell }$ and is only valid for systems with long-range positional order — crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] It is the modulus squared $|F_{hk\ell }|^{2}$ that gives the scattering intensity. $F_{hk\ell }$ is defined for a perfect crystal, and is used in crystallography, while $S(\mathbf {q} )$ is most useful for disordered systems.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] For partially ordered systems such as crystalline polymers there is obviously overlap, and experts will switch from one expression to the other as needed.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The static structure factor is measured without resolving the energy of scattered photons/electrons/neutrons.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Energy-resolved measurements yield the dynamic structure factor.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Consider the scattering of a beam of wavelength $\lambda$ by an assembly of N particles or atoms stationary at positions $\textstyle \mathbf {R} _{j},j=1,\,\ldots ,\,N$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Assume that the scattering is weak, so that the amplitude of the incident beam is constant throughout the sample volume (Born approximation), and absorption, refraction and multiple scattering can be neglected (kinematic diffraction).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The direction of any scattered wave is defined by its scattering vector $\mathbf {q}$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This vector is $\mathbf {q} =\mathbf {k_{s}} -\mathbf {k_{o}}$ , where $\mathbf {k_{s}}$ and $\mathbf {k_{o}}$ ( $|\mathbf {k_{s}} |=|\mathbf {k_{0}} |=2\pi /\lambda$ ) are the scattered and incident beam wavevectors, and $\theta$ is the angle between them.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] For an assembly of atoms, $f_{j}$ is the atomic form factor of the j -th atom.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Another useful simplification is if the material is isotropic, like a powder or a simple liquid.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] An alternative derivation gives good insight, but uses Fourier transforms and convolution.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] To be general, consider a scalar (real) quantity $\phi (\mathbf {r} )$ defined in a volume V ; this may correspond, for instance, to a mass or charge distribution or to the refractive index of an inhomogeneous medium.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] If the scalar function is integrable, we can write its Fourier transform as $\textstyle \psi (\mathbf {q} )=\int _{V}\phi (\mathbf {r} )\exp(-i\mathbf {q} \cdot \mathbf {r} )\,\mathrm {d} \mathbf {r}$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In the Born approximation the amplitude of the scattered wave corresponding to the scattering vector $\mathbf {q}$ is proportional to the Fourier transform $\textstyle \psi (\mathbf {q} )$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] with $\textstyle \mathbf {R} _{j},j=1,\,\ldots ,\,N$ the particle positions as before.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This is clearly the same as Equation (**1**) with all particles identical, except that here f is shown explicitly as a function of $\mathbf {q}$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In general, the particle positions are not fixed and the measurement takes place over a finite exposure time and with a macroscopic sample (much larger than the interparticle distance).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The experimentally accessible intensity is thus an averaged one $\textstyle \langle I(\mathbf {q} )\rangle$ ; we need not specify whether $\langle \cdot \rangle$ denotes a time or ensemble average.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In a crystal, the constitutive particles are arranged periodically, with translational symmetry forming a lattice.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The crystal structure can be described as a Bravais lattice with a group of atoms, called the basis, placed at every lattice point; that is, [crystal structure] = [lattice] $\ast$ [basis].
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] If the lattice is infinite and completely regular, the system is a perfect crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] For such a system, only a set of specific values for $\mathbf {q}$ can give scattering, and the scattering amplitude for all other values is zero.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This set of values forms a lattice, called the reciprocal lattice, which is the Fourier transform of the real-space crystal lattice.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The structure factor is then simply the squared modulus of the Fourier transform of the lattice, and shows the directions in which scattering can have non-zero intensity.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] At these values of $\mathbf {q}$ the wave from every lattice point is in phase.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The value of the structure factor is the same for all these reciprocal lattice points, and the intensity varies only due to changes in f with $\mathbf {q}$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The units of the structure-factor amplitude depend on the incident radiation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] For X-ray crystallography they are multiples of the unit of scattering by a single electron (2.82 $\times 10^{-15}$ m); for neutron scattering by atomic nuclei the unit of scattering length of $10^{-14}$ m is commonly used.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The above discussion uses the wave vectors $|\mathbf {k} |=2\pi /\lambda$ and $|\mathbf {q} |=4\pi \sin \theta /\lambda$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] However, crystallography often uses wave vectors $|\mathbf {s} |=1/\lambda$ and $|\mathbf {g} |=2\sin \theta /\lambda$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Therefore, when comparing equations from different sources, the factor $2\pi$ may appear and disappear, and care to maintain consistent quantities is required to get correct numerical results.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In crystallography, the basis and lattice are treated separately.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] where the sum is over all atoms in the unit cell, $x_{j},y_{j},z_{j}$ are the positional coordinates of the j -th atom, and $f_{j}$ is the scattering factor of the j -th atom.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The coordinates $x_{j},y_{j},z_{j}$ have the directions and dimensions of the lattice vectors $\mathbf {a} ,\mathbf {b} ,\mathbf {c}$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] $F_{hk\ell }$ is the vector sum of waves from all atoms within the unit cell.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] An atom at any lattice point has the reference phase angle zero for all $hk\ell$ since then $(hx_{j}+ky_{j}+\ell z_{j})$ is always an integer.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] A wave scattered from an atom at (1/2, 0, 0) will be in phase if h is even, out of phase if h is odd.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Again an alternative view using convolution can be helpful.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Since [crystal structure] = [lattice] $\ast$ [basis], ${\mathcal {F}}$ [crystal structure] = ${\mathcal {F}}$ [lattice] $\times {\mathcal {F}}$ [basis]; that is, scattering $\propto$ [reciprocal lattice] $\times$ [structure factor].
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The FCC lattice is a Bravais lattice, and its Fourier transform is a body-centered cubic lattice.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The most intense diffraction peak from a material that crystallizes in the FCC structure is typically the (111).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Films of FCC materials like gold tend to grow in a (111) orientation with a triangular surface symmetry.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] A zero diffracted intensity for a group of diffracted beams (here, $h,k,\ell$ of mixed parity) is called a systematic absence.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The diamond cubic crystal structure occurs for example in diamond (carbon), tin, and most semiconductors.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] There are 8 atoms in the cubic unit cell.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] But comparing this to the FCC above, we see that it is simpler to describe the structure as FCC with a basis of two atoms at (0, 0, 0) and (1/4, 1/4, 1/4).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The zincblende structure is similar to the diamond structure except that it is a compound of two distinct interpenetrating fcc lattices, rather than all the same element.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Cesium chloride is a simple cubic crystal lattice with a basis of Cs at (0,0,0) and Cl at (1/2, 1/2, 1/2) (or the other way around, it makes no difference).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The reciprocal lattice is easily constructed in one dimension: for particles on a line with a period a , the reciprocal lattice is an infinite array of points with spacing $2\pi /a$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In two dimensions, there are only five Bravais lattices.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The corresponding reciprocal lattices have the same symmetry as the direct lattice.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] 2-D lattices are excellent for demonstrating simple diffraction geometry on a flat screen, as below.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Equations (1)–(7) for structure factor $S(\mathbf {q} )$ apply with a scattering vector of limited dimensionality and a crystallographic structure factor can be defined in 2-D as $F_{hk}=\sum _{j=1}^{N}f_{j}\mathrm {e} ^{[-2\pi i(hx_{j}+ky_{j})]}$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] However, recall that real 2-D crystals such as graphene exist in 3-D.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The reciprocal lattice of a 2-D hexagonal sheet that exists in 3-D space in the $xy$ plane is a hexagonal array of lines parallel to the z or $z^{*}$ axis that extend to $\pm \infty$ and intersect any plane of constant z in a hexagonal array of points.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The Figure shows the construction of one vector of a 2-D reciprocal lattice and its relation to a scattering experiment.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] A parallel beam, with wave vector $\mathbf {k} _{i}$ is incident on a square lattice of parameter a .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The scattered wave is detected at a certain angle, which defines the wave vector of the outgoing beam, $\mathbf {k} _{o}$ (under the assumption of elastic scattering, $|\mathbf {k} _{o}|=|\mathbf {k} _{i}|$ ).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] One can equally define the scattering vector $\mathbf {q} =\mathbf {k} _{o}-\mathbf {k} _{i}$ and construct the harmonic pattern $\exp(i\mathbf {q} \mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In the depicted example, the spacing of this pattern coincides to the distance between particle rows: $q=2\pi /a$ , so that contributions to the scattering from all particles are in phase (constructive interference).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Thus, the total signal in direction $\mathbf {k} _{o}$ is strong, and $\mathbf {q}$ belongs to the reciprocal lattice.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] It is easily shown that this configuration fulfills Bragg's law.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Technically a perfect crystal must be infinite, so a finite size is an imperfection.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Real crystals always exhibit imperfections of their order besides their finite size, and these imperfections can have profound effects on the properties of the material.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] André Guinier proposed a widely employed distinction between imperfections that preserve the long-range order of the crystal that he called *disorder of the first kind* and those that destroy it called *disorder of the second kind*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] An example of the first is thermal vibration; an example of the second is some density of dislocations.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The generally applicable structure factor $S(\mathbf {q} )$ can be used to include the effect of any imperfection.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In crystallography, these effects are treated as separate from the structure factor $F_{hkl}$ , so separate factors for size or thermal effects are introduced into the expressions for scattered intensity, leaving the perfect crystal structure factor unchanged.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Therefore, a detailed description of these factors in crystallographic structure modeling and structure determination by diffraction is not appropriate in this article.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] For $S(q)$ a finite crystal means that the sums in equations 1-7 are now over a finite N .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The effect is most easily demonstrated with a 1-D lattice of points.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This function is shown in the Figure for different values of N .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] When the scattering from every particle is in phase, which is when the scattering is at a reciprocal lattice point $q=2k\pi /a$ , the sum of the amplitudes must be $\propto N$ and so the maxima in intensity are $\propto N^{2}$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Taking the above expression for $S(q)$ and estimating the limit $S(q\to 0)$ using, for instance, L'Hôpital's rule) shows that $S(q=2k\pi /a)=N$ as seen in the Figure.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] At the midpoint $S(q=(2k+1)\pi /a)=1/N$ (by direct evaluation) and the peak width decreases like $1/N$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In the large N limit, the peaks become infinitely sharp Dirac delta functions, the reciprocal lattice of the perfect 1-D lattice.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In crystallography when $F_{hkl}$ is used, N is large, and the formal size effect on diffraction is taken as $\left[{\frac {\sin(Nqa/2)}{(qa/2)}}\right]^{2}$ , which is the same as the expression for $S(q)$ above near to the reciprocal lattice points, $q\approx 2k\pi /a$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Using convolution, we can describe the finite real crystal structure as [lattice] $\ast$ [basis] $\times$ rectangular function, where the rectangular function has a value 1 inside the crystal and 0 outside it.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Then ${\mathcal {F}}$ [crystal structure] = ${\mathcal {F}}$ [lattice] $\times {\mathcal {F}}$ [basis] $\ast {F}$ [rectangular function]; that is, scattering $\propto$ [reciprocal lattice] $\times$ [structure factor] $\ast$ [ sinc function].
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Thus the intensity, which is a delta function of position for the perfect crystal, becomes a ${\textstyle \operatorname {sinc} ^{2}}$ function around every point with a maximum $\propto N^{2}$ , a width $\propto 1/N$ , area $\propto N$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This model for disorder in a crystal starts with the structure factor of a perfect crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] where the disorder is measured by the mean-square displacement of the positions $x_{j}$ from their positions in a perfect one-dimensional lattice: $a(j-(N-1)/2)$ , i.e., $x_{j}=a(j-(N-1)/2)+\delta x$ , where $\delta x$ is a small (much less than a ) random displacement.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] For disorder of the first kind, each random displacement $\delta x$ is independent of the others, and with respect to a perfect lattice.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Thus the displacements $\delta x$ do not destroy the translational order of the crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This has the consequence that for infinite crystals ( $N\to \infty$ ) the structure factor still has delta-function Bragg peaks – the peak width still goes to zero as $N\to \infty$ , with this kind of disorder.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] However, it does reduce the amplitude of the peaks, and due to the factor of $q^{2}$ in the exponential factor, it reduces peaks at large q much more than peaks at small q .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The structure is simply reduced by a q and disorder dependent term because all disorder of the first-kind does is smear out the scattering planes, effectively reducing the form factor.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In three dimensions the effect is the same, the structure is again reduced by a multiplicative factor, and this factor is often called the Debye–Waller factor.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Note that the Debye–Waller factor is often ascribed to thermal motion, i.e., the $\delta x$ are due to thermal motion, but any random displacements about a perfect lattice, not just thermal ones, will contribute to the Debye–Waller factor.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] However, fluctuations that cause the correlations between pairs of atoms to decrease as their separation increases, causes the Bragg peaks in the structure factor of a crystal to broaden.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] To see how this works, we consider a one-dimensional toy model: a stack of plates with mean spacing a .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] The derivation follows that in chapter 9 of Guinier's textbook.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This model has been pioneered by and applied to a number of materials by Hosemann and collaborators over a number of years.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Guinier and they termed this disorder of the second kind, and Hosemann in particular referred to this imperfect crystalline ordering as paracrystalline ordering.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Disorder of the first kind is the source of the Debye–Waller factor.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] To start with we will consider, for simplicity an infinite crystal, i.e., $N\to \infty$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] We will consider a finite crystal with disorder of the second-type below.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] For our infinite crystal, we want to consider pairs of lattice sites.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] For large each plane of an infinite crystal, there are two neighbours m planes away, so the above double sum becomes a single sum over pairs of neighbours either side of an atom, at positions $-m$ and m lattice spacings away, times N .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] where $p_{m}(\Delta x)$ is the probability density function for the separation $\Delta x$ of a pair of planes, m lattice spacings apart.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] and we also assume that the fluctuations between a plane and its neighbour, and between this neighbour and the next plane, are independent.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Then $p_{2}(\Delta x)$ is just the convolution of two $p_{1}(\Delta x)$ s, etc.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] i.e., the height of successive peaks drop off as the order of the peak (and so q ) squared.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Unlike finite-size effects that broaden peaks but do not decrease their height, disorder lowers peak heights.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Note that here we assuming that the disorder is relatively weak, so that we still have relatively well defined peaks.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] which is a Lorentzian or Cauchy function, of FWHM $q_{P}^{2}\sigma _{2}^{2}/a=4\pi ^{2}n^{2}(\sigma _{2}/a)^{2}/a$ , i.e., the FWHM increases as the square of the order of peak, and so as the square of the wave vector q at the peak.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Finally, the product of the peak height and the FWHM is constant and equals $4/a$ , in the $q\sigma _{2}\ll 1$ limit.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] For the first few peaks where n is not large, this is just the $\sigma _{2}/a\ll 1$ limit.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] where the factor in parentheses comes from the fact the sum is over nearest-neighbour pairs ( $m=1$ ), next nearest-neighbours ( $m=2$ ), ... and for a crystal of N planes, there are $N-1$ pairs of nearest neighbours, $N-2$ pairs of next-nearest neighbours, etc.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In contrast with crystals, liquids have no long-range order (in particular, there is no regular lattice), so the structure factor does not exhibit sharp peaks.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] They do however show a certain degree of short-range order, depending on their density and on the strength of the interaction between particles.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Liquids are isotropic, so that, after the averaging operation in Equation (**4**), the structure factor only depends on the absolute magnitude of the scattering vector $q=\left|\mathbf {q} \right|$ .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Even for interacting particles, at high scattering vector the structure factor goes to 1.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This result follows from Equation (**10**), since $S(q)-1$ is the Fourier transform of the "regular" function $g(r)$ and thus goes to zero for high values of the argument q .
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This reasoning does not hold for a perfect crystal, where the distribution function exhibits infinitely sharp peaks.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In the hard sphere model, the particles are described as impenetrable spheres with radius R ; thus, their center-to-center distance $r\geq 2R$ and they experience no interaction beyond this distance.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] This model has an analytical solution in the Percus–Yevick approximation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Although highly simplified, it provides a good description for systems ranging from liquid metals to colloidal suspensions.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In an illustration, the structure factor for a hard-sphere fluid is shown in the Figure, for volume fractions $\Phi$ from 1% to 40%.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] In polymer systems, the general definition (**4**) holds; the elementary constituents are now the monomers making up the chains.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] However, the structure factor being a measure of the correlation between particle positions, one can reasonably expect that this correlation will be different for monomers belonging to the same chain or to different chains.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] Let us assume that the volume V contains $N_{c}$ identical molecules, each composed of $N_{p}$ monomers, such that $N_{c}N_{p}=N$ ( $N_{p}$ is also known as the degree of polymerization).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] where indices $\alpha ,\beta$ label the different molecules and $j,k$ the different monomers along each molecule.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] On the right-hand side we separated *intramolecular* ( $\alpha =\beta$ ) and *intermolecular* ( $\alpha \neq \beta$ ) terms.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/structure-factor] where $S_{1}(q)$ is the single-chain structure factor.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography has been fundamental in the development of many scientific fields.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In its first decades of use, this method determined the size of atoms, the lengths and types of chemical bonds, and the atomic-scale differences between various materials, especially minerals and alloys.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The method has also revealed the structure and function of many biological molecules, including vitamins, drugs, proteins and nucleic acids such as DNA, as well as viruses.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography is still the primary method for characterizing the atomic structure of materials and in differentiating materials that appear similar in other experiments.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystal structures can also help explain unusual electronic or elastic properties of a material, shed light on chemical interactions and processes, or serve as the basis for designing pharmaceuticals against diseases.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Modern work involves a number of steps all of which are important.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The preliminary steps include preparing good quality samples, careful recording of the diffracted intensities, and processing of the data to remove artifacts.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A variety of different methods are then used to obtain an estimate of the atomic structure, generically called direct methods.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] With an initial estimate further computational techniques such as those involving difference maps are used to complete the structure.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The final step is a numerical refinement of the atomic positions against the experimental data, sometimes assisted by *ab-initio* calculations.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In almost all cases new structures are deposited in databases available to the international community.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Crystals, though long admired for their regularity and symmetry, were not investigated scientifically until the 17th century.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Johannes Kepler hypothesized in his work *Strena seu de Nive Sexangula* (A New Year's Gift of Hexagonal Snow) (1611) that the hexagonal symmetry of snowflake crystals was due to a regular packing of spherical water particles.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The Danish scientist Nicolas Steno (1669) pioneered experimental investigations of crystal symmetry.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Steno showed that the angles between the faces are the same in every exemplar of a particular type of crystal (law of constancy of interfacial angles).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] René Just Haüy (1784) discovered that every face of a crystal can be described by simple stacking patterns of blocks of the same shape and size (law of decrements).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Hence, William Hallowes Miller in 1839 was able to give each face a unique label of three small integers, the Miller indices which remain in use for identifying crystal faces.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Haüy's study led to the idea that crystals are a regular three-dimensional array (a Bravais lattice) of atoms and molecules; a single unit cell is repeated indefinitely along three principal directions.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In the 19th century, a complete catalog of the possible symmetries of a crystal was worked out by Johan Hessel, Auguste Bravais, Evgraf Fedorov, Arthur Schönflies and (belatedly) William Barlow (1894).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Barlow proposed several crystal structures in the 1880s that were validated later by X-ray crystallography; however, the available data were too scarce in the 1880s to accept his models as conclusive.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Wilhelm Röntgen discovered X-rays in 1895.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Physicists were uncertain of the nature of X-rays, but suspected that they were waves of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The Maxwell theory of electromagnetic radiation was well accepted, and experiments by Charles Glover Barkla showed that X-rays exhibited phenomena associated with electromagnetic waves, including transverse polarization and spectral lines akin to those observed in the visible wavelengths.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] X-rays are not only waves but also have particle properties causing Sommerfeld to coin the name Bremsstrahlung for the continuous spectra when they were formed when electrons bombarded a material.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Albert Einstein introduced the photon concept in 1905, but it was not broadly accepted until 1922, when Arthur Compton confirmed it by the scattering of X-rays from electrons.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The particle-like properties of X-rays, such as their ionization of gases, had prompted William Henry Bragg to argue in 1907 that X-rays were *not* electromagnetic radiation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Bragg's view proved unpopular and the observation of X-ray diffraction by Max von Laue in 1912 confirmed that X-rays are a form of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The idea that crystals could be used as a diffraction grating for X-rays arose in 1912 in a conversation between Paul Peter Ewald and Max von Laue in the English Garden in Munich.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Ewald had proposed a resonator model of crystals for his thesis, but this model could not be validated using visible light, since the wavelength was much larger than the spacing between the resonators.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Von Laue realized that electromagnetic radiation of a shorter wavelength was needed, and suggested that X-rays might have a wavelength comparable to the unit-cell spacing in crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Von Laue worked with two technicians, Walter Friedrich and his assistant Paul Knipping, to shine a beam of X-rays through a copper sulfate crystal and record its diffraction on a photographic plate.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] After being developed, the plate showed a large number of well-defined spots arranged in a pattern of intersecting circles around the spot produced by the central beam.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The results were presented to the Bavarian Academy of Sciences and Humanities in June 1912 as "Interferenz-Erscheinungen bei Röntgenstrahlen" (Interference phenomena in X-rays).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Von Laue developed a law that connects the scattering angles and the size and orientation of the unit-cell spacings in the crystal, for which he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1914.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] After Von Laue's pioneering research, the field developed rapidly, most notably by contributions from physicists William Lawrence Bragg and his father William Henry Bragg.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In 1912–1913, the younger Bragg developed Bragg's law, which connects the scattering with evenly spaced planes within a crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The Braggs, father and son, shared the 1915 Nobel Prize in Physics for their work in crystallography.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The earliest structures were generally simple; as computational and experimental methods improved over the next decades, it became feasible to deduce reliable atomic positions for more complicated arrangements of atoms.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The earliest structures were simple inorganic crystals and minerals, but even these revealed fundamental laws of physics and chemistry.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The first atomic-resolution structure to be "solved" (i.e., determined) in 1914 was that of table salt.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The distribution of electrons in the table-salt structure showed that crystals are not necessarily composed of covalently bonded molecules, and proved the existence of ionic compounds.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The structure of diamond was solved in the same year, proving the tetrahedral arrangement of its chemical bonds and showing that the length of C–C single bond was about 1.52 angstroms.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Other early structures included copper, calcium fluoride (CaF2, also known as *fluorite*), calcite (CaCO3) and pyrite (FeS2) in 1914; spinel (MgAl2O4) in 1915; the rutile and anatase forms of titanium dioxide (TiO2) in 1916; pyrochroite (Mn(OH)2) and, by extension, brucite (Mg(OH)2) in 1919.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Also in 1919, sodium nitrate (NaNO3) and caesium dichloroiodate (CsICl2) were determined by Ralph Walter Graystone Wyckoff, and the wurtzite (hexagonal ZnS) structure was determined in 1920.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The structure of graphite was solved in 1916 by the related method of powder diffraction, which was developed by Peter Debye and Paul Scherrer and, independently, by Albert Hull in 1917.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The structure of graphite was determined from single-crystal diffraction in 1924 by two groups independently.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Hull also used the powder method to determine the structures of various metals, such as iron and magnesium.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography has led to a better understanding of chemical bonds and non-covalent interactions.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Her conclusions were anticipated by William Henry Bragg, who published models of naphthalene and anthracene in 1921 based on other molecules, an early form of molecular replacement.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The first structure of an organic compound, hexamethylenetetramine, was solved in 1923.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] This was rapidly followed by several studies of different long-chain fatty acids, which are an important component of biological membranes.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In the 1930s, the structures of much larger molecules with two-dimensional complexity began to be solved.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A significant advance was the structure of phthalocyanine, a large planar molecule that is closely related to porphyrin molecules important in biology, such as heme, corrin and chlorophyll.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In the 1920s, Victor Moritz Goldschmidt and later Linus Pauling developed rules for eliminating chemically unlikely structures and for determining the relative sizes of atoms.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] These rules led to the structure of brookite (1928) and an understanding of the relative stability of the rutile, brookite and anatase forms of titanium dioxide.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography—or, strictly speaking, an inelastic Compton scattering experiment—has also provided evidence for the partly covalent character of hydrogen bonds.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In the field of organometallic chemistry, the X-ray structure of ferrocene initiated scientific studies of sandwich compounds, while that of Zeise's salt stimulated research into "back bonding" and metal-pi complexes.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Finally, X-ray crystallography had a pioneering role in the development of supramolecular chemistry, particularly in clarifying the structures of the crown ethers and the principles of host–guest chemistry.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Many complicated inorganic and organometallic systems have been analyzed using single-crystal methods, such as fullerenes, metalloporphyrins, and other complicated compounds.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Single-crystal diffraction is also used in the pharmaceutical industry.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The Cambridge Structural Database contains over 1,000,000 structures as of June 2019; most of these structures were determined by X-ray crystallography.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The application of X-ray crystallography to mineralogy began with the structure of garnet, which was determined in 1924 by Menzer.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A systematic X-ray crystallographic study of the silicates was undertaken in the 1920s.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] This study showed that, as the Si/O ratio is altered, the silicate crystals exhibit significant changes in their atomic arrangements.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Machatschki extended these insights to minerals in which aluminium substitutes for the silicon atoms of the silicates.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The first application of X-ray crystallography to metallurgy also occurred in the mid-1920s.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Most notably, Linus Pauling's structure of the alloy Mg2Sn led to his theory of the stability and structure of complex ionic crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] On October 17, 2012, the Curiosity rover on the planet Mars at "Rocknest" performed the first X-ray diffraction analysis of Martian soil.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The results from the rover's CheMin analyzer revealed the presence of several minerals, including feldspar, pyroxenes and olivine, and suggested that the Martian soil in the sample was similar to the "weathered basaltic soils" of Hawaiian volcanoes.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography of biological molecules took off with Dorothy Crowfoot Hodgkin, who solved the structures of cholesterol (1937), penicillin (1946) and vitamin B12 (1956), for which she was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1964.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In 1969, she succeeded in solving the structure of insulin, on which she worked for over thirty years.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Crystal structures of proteins (which are irregular and hundreds of times larger than cholesterol) began to be solved in the late 1950s, beginning with the structure of sperm whale myoglobin by Sir John Cowdery Kendrew, for which he shared the Nobel Prize in Chemistry with Max Perutz in 1962.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Since that success, 190,000 X-ray crystal structures of proteins, nucleic acids and other biological molecules have been determined.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The nearest competing method in number of structures analyzed is nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy, which has resolved less than one tenth as many.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Crystallography can solve structures of arbitrarily large molecules, whereas solution-state NMR is restricted to relatively small ones (less than 70 kDa).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography is used routinely to determine how a pharmaceutical drug interacts with its protein target and what changes might improve it.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] However, intrinsic membrane proteins remain challenging to crystallize because they require detergents or other denaturants to solubilize them in isolation, and such detergents often interfere with crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Membrane proteins are a large component of the genome, and include many proteins of great physiological importance, such as ion channels and receptors.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Helium cryogenics are used to reduce radiation damage in protein crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Two limiting cases of X-ray crystallography—"small-molecule" (which includes continuous inorganic solids) and "macromolecular" crystallography—are often used.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Small-molecule crystallography typically involves crystals with fewer than 100 atoms in their asymmetric unit; such crystal structures are usually so well resolved that the atoms can be discerned as isolated "blobs" of electron density.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In contrast, macromolecular crystallography often involves tens of thousands of atoms in the unit cell.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Such crystal structures are generally less well-resolved; the atoms and chemical bonds appear as tubes of electron density, rather than as isolated atoms.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In general, small molecules are also easier to crystallize than macromolecules; however, X-ray crystallography has proven possible even for viruses and proteins with hundreds of thousands of atoms, through improved crystallographic imaging and technology.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The technique of single-crystal X-ray crystallography has three basic steps.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The first—and often most difficult—step is to obtain an adequate crystal of the material under study.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The crystal should be sufficiently large (typically larger than 0.1 mm in all dimensions), pure in composition and regular in structure, with no significant internal imperfections such as cracks or twinning.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In the second step, the crystal is placed in an intense beam of X-rays, usually of a single wavelength (*monochromatic X-rays*), producing the regular pattern of reflections.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The angles and intensities of diffracted X-rays are measured, with each compound having a unique diffraction pattern.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] As the crystal is gradually rotated, previous reflections disappear and new ones appear; the intensity of every spot is recorded at every orientation of the crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Multiple data sets may have to be collected, with each set covering slightly more than half a full rotation of the crystal and typically containing tens of thousands of reflections.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In the third step, these data are combined computationally with complementary chemical information to produce and refine a model of the arrangement of atoms within the crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The final, refined model of the atomic arrangement—now called a *crystal structure*—is usually stored in a public database.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Although crystallography can be used to characterize the disorder in an impure or irregular crystal, crystallography generally requires a pure crystal of high regularity to solve the structure of a complicated arrangement of atoms.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Pure, regular crystals can sometimes be obtained from natural or synthetic materials, such as samples of metals, minerals or other macroscopic materials.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The regularity of such crystals can sometimes be improved with macromolecular crystal annealing and other methods.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] However, in many cases, obtaining a diffraction-quality crystal is the chief barrier to solving its atomic-resolution structure.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Small-molecule and macromolecular crystallography differ in the range of possible techniques used to produce diffraction-quality crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Small molecules generally have few degrees of conformational freedom, and may be crystallized by a wide range of methods, such as chemical vapor deposition and recrystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] By contrast, macromolecules generally have many degrees of freedom and their crystallization must be carried out so as to maintain a stable structure.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] For example, proteins and larger RNA molecules cannot be crystallized if their tertiary structure has been unfolded; therefore, the range of crystallization conditions is restricted to solution conditions in which such molecules remain folded.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Protein crystals are almost always grown in solution.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The most common approach is to lower the solubility of its component molecules very gradually; if this is done too quickly, the molecules will precipitate from solution, forming a useless dust or amorphous gel on the bottom of the container.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Crystal growth in solution is characterized by two steps: *nucleation* of a microscopic crystallite (possibly having only 100 molecules), followed by *growth* of that crystallite, ideally to a diffraction-quality crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The solution conditions that favor the first step (nucleation) are not always the same conditions that favor the second step (subsequent growth).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The solution conditions should *disfavor* the first step (nucleation) but *favor* the second (growth), so that only one large crystal forms per droplet.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] If nucleation is favored too much, a shower of small crystallites will form in the droplet, rather than one large crystal; if favored too little, no crystal will form whatsoever.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Other approaches involve crystallizing proteins under oil, where aqueous protein solutions are dispensed under liquid oil, and water evaporates through the layer of oil.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Different oils have different evaporation permeabilities, therefore yielding changes in concentration rates from different percipient/protein mixture.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] It is difficult to predict good conditions for nucleation or growth of well-ordered crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In practice, favorable conditions are identified by *screening*; a very large batch of the molecules is prepared, and a wide variety of crystallization solutions are tested.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Hundreds, even thousands, of solution conditions are generally tried before finding the successful one.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] It is also common to try several temperatures for encouraging crystallization, or to gradually lower the temperature so that the solution becomes supersaturated.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] These methods require large amounts of the target molecule, as they use high concentration of the molecule(s) to be crystallized.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Due to the difficulty in obtaining such large quantities (milligrams) of crystallization-grade protein, robots have been developed that are capable of accurately dispensing crystallization trial drops that are in the order of 100 nanoliters in volume.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] This means that 10-fold less protein is used per experiment when compared to crystallization trials set up by hand (in the order of 1 microliter).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Several factors are known to inhibit crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The growing crystals are generally held at a constant temperature and protected from shocks or vibrations that might disturb their crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Impurities in the molecules or in the crystallization solutions are often inimical to crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Conformational flexibility in the molecule also tends to make crystallization less likely, due to entropy.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Molecules that tend to self-assemble into regular helices are often unwilling to assemble into crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Crystals can be marred by twinning, which can occur when a unit cell can pack equally favorably in multiple orientations; although recent advances in computational methods may allow solving the structure of some twinned crystals.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Having failed to crystallize a target molecule, a crystallographer may try again with a slightly modified version of the molecule; even small changes in molecular properties can lead to large differences in crystallization behavior.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] For proteins, impurities have been shown to sometimes enhance and sometimes disrupt crystal growth.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Oscillation with audible sound sometimes works.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] These issues may be related to the phase separation characteristic of protein crystalation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The crystal is mounted for measurements so that it may be held in the X-ray beam and rotated.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In the past, crystals were loaded into glass capillaries with the crystallization solution (the mother liquor).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Crystals of small molecules are typically attached with oil or glue to a glass fiber or a loop, which is made of nylon or plastic and attached to a solid rod.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Protein crystals are scooped up by a loop, then flash-frozen with liquid nitrogen.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] This freezing reduces the radiation damage of the X-rays, as well as thermal motion (the Debye-Waller effect).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] However, untreated protein crystals often crack if flash-frozen; therefore, they are generally pre-soaked in a cryoprotectant solution before freezing.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] This pre-soak may itself cause the crystal to crack, ruining it for crystallography.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Generally, successful cryo-conditions are identified by trial and error.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The capillary or loop is mounted on a goniometer, which allows it to be positioned accurately within the X-ray beam and rotated.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Since both the crystal and the beam are often very small, the crystal must be centered within the beam to within ~25 micrometers accuracy, which is aided by a camera focused on the crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The most common type of goniometer is the "kappa goniometer", which offers three angles of rotation: the ω angle, which rotates about an axis perpendicular to the beam; the κ angle, about an axis at ~50° to the ω axis; and, finally, the φ angle about the loop/capillary axis.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] When the κ angle is zero, the ω and φ axes are aligned.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The κ rotation allows for convenient mounting of the crystal, since the arm in which the crystal is mounted may be swung out towards the crystallographer.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The oscillations carried out during data collection (mentioned below) involve the ω axis only.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] An older type of goniometer is the four-circle goniometer, and its relatives such as the six-circle goniometer.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The relative intensities of the reflections provides information to determine the arrangement of molecules within the crystal in atomic detail.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The intensities of these reflections may be recorded with photographic film, an area detector (such as a pixel detector) or with a charge-coupled device (CCD) image sensor.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The peaks at small angles correspond to low-resolution data, whereas those at high angles represent high-resolution data; thus, an upper limit on the eventual resolution of the structure can be determined from the first few images.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Some measures of diffraction quality can be determined at this point, such as the mosaicity of the crystal and its overall disorder, as observed in the peak widths.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Some pathologies of the crystal that would render it unfit for solving the structure can also be diagnosed quickly at this point.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] One set of spots is insufficient to reconstruct the whole crystal; it represents only a small slice of the full three dimensional set.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] To collect all the necessary information, the crystal must be rotated step-by-step through 180°, with an image recorded at every step; actually, slightly more than 180° is required to cover reciprocal space, due to the curvature of the Ewald sphere.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] However, if the crystal has a higher symmetry, a smaller angular range such as 90° or 45° may be recorded.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The rotation axis should be changed at least once, to avoid developing a "blind spot" in reciprocal space close to the rotation axis.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] It is customary to rock the crystal slightly (by 0.5–2°) to catch a broader region of reciprocal space.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Multiple data sets may be necessary for certain phasing methods.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] For example, multi-wavelength anomalous dispersion phasing requires that the scattering be recorded at least three (and usually four, for redundancy) wavelengths of the incoming X-ray radiation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A single crystal may degrade too much during the collection of one data set, owing to radiation damage; in such cases, data sets on multiple crystals must be taken.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The recorded series of two-dimensional diffraction patterns, each corresponding to a different crystal orientation, is converted into a three-dimensional set.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Data processing begins with *indexing* the reflections.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] This means identifying the dimensions of the unit cell and which image peak corresponds to which position in reciprocal space.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A byproduct of indexing is to determine the symmetry of the crystal, i.e., its *space group*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Some space groups can be eliminated from the beginning.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] For example, reflection symmetries cannot be observed in chiral molecules; thus, only 65 space groups of 230 possible are allowed for protein molecules which are almost always chiral.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Indexing is generally accomplished using an *autoindexing* routine.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Having assigned symmetry, the data is then *integrated*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A full data set may consist of hundreds of separate images taken at different orientations of the crystal.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] These have to be merged and scaled using peaks that appear in two or more images (*merging*) and scaling so there is a consistent intensity scale.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Optimizing the intensity scale is critical because the relative intensity of the peaks is the key information from which the structure is determined.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The repetitive technique of crystallographic data collection and the often high symmetry of crystalline materials cause the diffractometer to record many symmetry-equivalent reflections multiple times.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] This allows calculating the symmetry-related R-factor, a reliability index based upon how similar are the measured intensities of symmetry-equivalent reflections, thus assessing the quality of the data.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The intensity of each diffraction 'spot' is proportional to the modulus squared of the structure factor.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The structure factor is a complex number containing information relating to both the amplitude and phase of a wave.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In order to obtain an interpretable *electron density map*, both amplitude and phase must be known (an electron density map allows a crystallographer to build a starting model of the molecule).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The phase cannot be directly recorded during a diffraction experiment: this is known as the phase problem.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Having obtained initial phases, an initial model can be built.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The atomic positions in the model and their respective Debye-Waller factors (or **B**-factors, accounting for the thermal motion of the atom) can be refined to fit the observed diffraction data, ideally yielding a better set of phases.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A new model can then be fit to the new electron density map and successive rounds of refinement are carried out.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] This iterative process continues until the correlation between the diffraction data and the model is maximized.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A similar quality criterion is *R*free, which is calculated from a subset (~10%) of reflections that were not included in the structure refinement.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Both *R* factors depend on the resolution of the data.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] As a rule of thumb, *R*free should be approximately the resolution in angstroms divided by 10; thus, a data-set with 2 Å resolution should yield a final *R*free ~ 0.2.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Chemical bonding features such as stereochemistry, hydrogen bonding and distribution of bond lengths and angles are complementary measures of the model quality.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In iterative model building, it is common to encounter phase bias or model bias: because phase estimations come from the model, each round of calculated map tends to show density wherever the model has density, regardless of whether there truly is a density.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] This problem can be mitigated by maximum-likelihood weighting and checking using *omit maps*.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] It may not be possible to observe every atom in the asymmetric unit.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In many cases, crystallographic disorder smears the electron density map.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Weakly scattering atoms such as hydrogen are routinely invisible.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] It is also possible for a single atom to appear multiple times in an electron density map, e.g., if a protein sidechain has multiple (<4) allowed conformations.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In still other cases, the crystallographer may detect that the covalent structure deduced for the molecule was incorrect, or changed.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] For example, proteins may be cleaved or undergo post-translational modifications that were not detected prior to the crystallization.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A common challenge in refinement of crystal structures results from crystallographic disorder.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Disorder can take many forms but in general involves the coexistence of two or more species or conformations.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Failure to recognize disorder results in flawed interpretation.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Pitfalls from improper modeling of disorder are illustrated by the discounted hypothesis of bond stretch isomerism.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Disorder is modelled with respect to the relative population of the components, often only two, and their identity.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In structures of large molecules and ions, solvent and counterions are often disordered.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] The use of computational methods for the powder X-ray diffraction data analysis is now generalized.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] It typically compares the experimental data to the simulated diffractogram of a model structure, taking into account the instrumental parameters, and refines the structural or microstructural parameters of the model using least squares based minimization algorithm.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Most of these tools also allow Le Bail refinement (also referred to as profile matching), that is, refinement of the cell parameters based on the Bragg peaks positions and peak profiles, without taking into account the crystallographic structure by itself.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] More recent tools allow the refinement of both structural and microstructural data, such as the FAULTS program included in the FullProf Suite, which allows the refinement of structures with planar defects (e.g. stacking faults, twinnings, intergrowths).
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Many structures obtained in private commercial ventures to crystallize medicinally relevant proteins are not deposited in public crystallographic databases.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] A number of women were pioneers in X-ray crystallography at a time when they were excluded from most other branches of physical science.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Kathleen Lonsdale was a research student of William Henry Bragg, who had 11 women research students out of a total of 18.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] She is known for both her experimental and theoretical work.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Lonsdale joined his crystallography research team at the Royal Institution in London in 1923, and after getting married and having children, went back to work with Bragg as a researcher.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Lonsdale always advocated greater participation of women in science and said in 1970: "Any country that wants to make full use of all its potential scientists and technologists could do so, but it must not expect to get the women quite so simply as it gets the men. ...
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] It is utopian, then, to suggest that any country that really wants married women to return to a scientific career, when her children no longer need her physical presence, should make special arrangements to encourage her to do so?".
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] During this period, Lonsdale began a collaboration with William T.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Astbury on a set of 230 space group tables which was published in 1924 and became an essential tool for crystallographers.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] In 1932 Dorothy Hodgkin joined the laboratory of the physicist John Desmond Bernal, who was a former student of Bragg, in Cambridge, UK.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] She and Bernal took the first X-ray photographs of crystalline proteins.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Hodgkin also played a role in the foundation of the International Union of Crystallography.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] She was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1964 for her work using X-ray techniques to study the structures of penicillin, insulin and vitamin B12.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Her work on penicillin began in 1942 during the war and on vitamin B12 in 1948.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] While her group slowly grew, their predominant focus was on the X-ray analysis of natural products.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] She is the only British woman ever to have won a Nobel Prize in a science subject.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Rosalind Franklin worked on the X-ray photography of a DNA fibre that proved key to James Watson and Francis Crick's discovery of the double helix, for which they both won the Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine in 1962.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Watson revealed in his autobiographic account of the discovery of the structure of DNA, *The Double Helix*, that he had used Franklin's X-ray photograph without her permission.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Franklin died of cancer in her 30s, before Watson received the Nobel Prize.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Franklin also carried out important structural studies of carbon in coal and graphite, and of plant and animal viruses.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Isabella Karle of the United States Naval Research Laboratory developed an experimental approach to the mathematical theory of crystallography.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Her work improved the speed and accuracy of chemical and biomedical analysis.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Yet only her husband Jerome shared the 1985 Nobel Prize in Chemistry with Herbert Hauptman, "for outstanding achievements in the development of direct methods for the determination of crystal structures".
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Other prize-giving bodies have showered Isabella with awards in her own right.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Women have written many textbooks and research papers in the field of X-ray crystallography.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] For many years Lonsdale edited the *International Tables for Crystallography*, which provide information on crystal lattices, symmetry, and space groups, as well as mathematical, physical and chemical data on structures.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Olga Kennard of the University of Cambridge, founded and ran the Cambridge Crystallographic Data Centre, an internationally recognized source of structural data on small molecules, from 1965 until 1997.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Jenny Pickworth Glusker, a British scientist, co-authored *Crystal Structure Analysis: A Primer*, first published in 1971 and as of 2010 in its third edition.
[src:x-ray-crystallography-protein/x-ray-crystallography] Eleanor Dodson, an Australian-born biologist, who began as Dorothy Hodgkin's technician, was the main instigator behind CCP4, the collaborative computing project that currently shares more than 250 software tools with protein crystallographers worldwide.
